P_HTM[6209]="*4.2. Katāpattivāra**4.2 The section on “how many offenses”*";
P_HTM[6210]="*Paṭhamena āpattisamuṭṭhānena kati āpattiyo āpajjati?**How many offenses does one commit through the first origin of offenses?*";
P_HTM[6211]="*Paṭhamena āpattisamuṭṭhānena pañca āpattiyo āpajjati.**Five:*";
P_HTM[6212]="*Bhikkhu kappiyasaññī saññācikāya kuṭiṃ karoti adesitavatthukaṃ pamāṇātikkantaṃ sārambhaṃ aparikkamanaṃ, payoge dukkaṭaṃ;**when a monk—perceiving it as allowable and by means of begging—builds a hut whose site has not been approved, which exceeds the right size, where harm will be done, and which lacks a space on all sides, then for the effort there is an offense of wrong conduct;*";
P_HTM[6213]="*ekaṃ piṇḍaṃ anāgate āpatti thullaccayassa;**when there is one piece left to complete the hut, he commits a serious offense;*";
P_HTM[6214]="*tasmiṃ piṇḍe āgate āpatti saṅghādisesassa;**when the last piece is finished, he commits an offense entailing suspension;*";
P_HTM[6215]="*bhikkhu kappiyasaññī vikāle bhojanaṃ bhuñjati, āpatti pācittiyassa;**when a monk, perceiving it as allowable, eats cooked food at the wrong time, he commits an offense entailing confession;*";
P_HTM[6216]="*bhikkhu kappiyasaññī aññātikāya bhikkhuniyā antaragharaṃ paviṭṭhāya hatthato khādanīyaṃ vā bhojanīyaṃ vā sahatthā paṭiggahetvā bhuñjati, āpatti pāṭidesanīyassa—**when a monk, perceiving it as allowable, receives fresh or cooked food directly from an unrelated nun who has entered an inhabited area, and then eats it, he commits an offense entailing acknowledgment.*";
P_HTM[6217]="*paṭhamena āpattisamuṭṭhānena imā pañca āpattiyo āpajjati.* **";
P_HTM[6218]="*Tā āpattiyo catunnaṃ vipattīnaṃ kati vipattiyo bhajanti?**When it comes to these offenses, to how many of the four kinds of failure do they belong?*";
P_HTM[6219]="*Sattannaṃ āpattikkhandhānaṃ katihi āpattikkhandhehi saṅgahitā?**In how many of the seven classes of offenses are they found?*";
P_HTM[6220]="*Channaṃ āpattisamuṭṭhānānaṃ katihi samuṭṭhānehi samuṭṭhanti?**Through how many of the six kinds of origins of offenses do they originate?*";
P_HTM[6221]="*Catunnaṃ adhikaraṇānaṃ katamaṃ adhikaraṇaṃ?**To which of the four kinds of legal issues do they belong?*";
P_HTM[6222]="*Sattannaṃ samathānaṃ katihi samathehi sammanti?**Through how many of the seven principles for settling legal issues are they settled?*";
P_HTM[6223]="*Tā āpattiyo catunnaṃ vipattīnaṃ dve vipattiyo bhajanti—**They belong to two kinds of failure:*";
P_HTM[6224]="*siyā sīlavipattiṃ, siyā ācāravipattiṃ.**they may be failure in morality; they may be failure in conduct.*";
P_HTM[6225]="*Sattannaṃ āpattikkhandhānaṃ pañcahi āpattikkhandhehi saṅgahitā—**They are found in five classes of offenses:*";
P_HTM[6226]="*siyā saṅghādisesāpattikkhandhena, siyā thullaccayāpattikkhandhena, siyā pācittiyāpattikkhandhena, siyā pāṭidesanīyāpattikkhandhena, siyā dukkaṭāpattikkhandhena.**they may be in the class of offenses entailing suspension; they may be in the class of serious offenses; they may be in the class of offenses entailing confession; they may be in the class of offenses entailing acknowledgment; they may be in the class of offenses of wrong conduct.*";
P_HTM[6227]="*Channaṃ āpattisamuṭṭhānānaṃ ekena samuṭṭhānena samuṭṭhanti—**They originate in one way:*";
P_HTM[6228]="*kāyato samuṭṭhanti, na vācato na cittato.**from body, not from speech or mind.*";
P_HTM[6229]="*Catunnaṃ adhikaraṇānaṃ āpattādhikaraṇaṃ.**They are legal issues arising from an offense.*";
P_HTM[6230]="*Sattannaṃ samathānaṃ tīhi samathehi sammanti—**They are settled in three ways:*";
P_HTM[6231]="*siyā sammukhāvinayena ca paṭiññātakaraṇena ca, siyā sammukhāvinayena ca tiṇavatthārakena ca.**they may be settled by resolution face-to-face and by acting according to what has been admitted; or they may be settled by resolution face-to-face and by covering over as if with grass.*";
P_HTM[6232]="*Dutiyena āpattisamuṭṭhānena kati āpattiyo āpajjati?**How many offenses does one commit through the second origin of offenses?*";
P_HTM[6233]="*Dutiyena āpattisamuṭṭhānena catasso āpattiyo āpajjati—**Four:*";
P_HTM[6234]="*bhikkhu kappiyasaññī samādisati—“kuṭiṃ me karothā”ti. Tassa kuṭiṃ karonti adesitavatthukaṃ pamāṇātikkantaṃ sārambhaṃ aparikkamanaṃ. Payoge dukkaṭaṃ;**when a monk, perceiving it as allowable, appoints someone to build him a hut, and they build a hut whose site has not been approved, which exceeds the right size, where harm will be done, and which lacks a space on all sides, then for the effort there is an offense of wrong conduct;*";
P_HTM[6235]="*ekaṃ piṇḍaṃ anāgate āpatti thullaccayassa;**when one piece is left to complete the hut, he commits a serious offense;*";
P_HTM[6236]="*tasmiṃ piṇḍe āgate āpatti saṅghādisesassa.**when the last piece is finished, he commits an offense entailing suspension;*";
P_HTM[6237]="*Bhikkhu kappiyasaññī anupasampannaṃ padaso dhammaṃ vāceti, āpatti pācittiyassa—**when a monk, perceiving it as allowable, instructs a person who is not fully ordained to memorize the Teaching, he commits an offense entailing confession.*";
P_HTM[6238]="*dutiyena āpattisamuṭṭhānena imā catasso āpattiyo āpajjati.* **";
P_HTM[6239]="*Tā āpattiyo catunnaṃ vipattīnaṃ kati vipattiyo bhajanti …pe…**When it comes to these offenses, to how many of the four kinds of failure do they belong? …*";
P_HTM[6240]="*sattannaṃ samathānaṃ katihi samathehi sammanti?**Through how many of the seven principles for settling legal issues are they settled?*";
P_HTM[6241]="*Tā āpattiyo catunnaṃ vipattīnaṃ dve vipattiyo bhajanti—**They belong to two kinds of failure:*";
P_HTM[6242]="*siyā sīlavipattiṃ, siyā ācāravipattiṃ.**they may be failure in morality; they may be failure in conduct.*";
P_HTM[6243]="*Sattannaṃ āpattikkhandhānaṃ catūhi āpattikkhandhehi saṅgahitā—**They are found in four classes of offenses:*";
P_HTM[6244]="*siyā saṅghādisesāpattikkhandhena, siyā thullaccayāpattikkhandhena, siyā pācittiyāpattikkhandhena, siyā dukkaṭāpattikkhandhena.**they may be in the class of offenses entailing suspension; they may be in the class of serious offenses; they may be in the class of offenses entailing confession; they may be in the class of offenses of wrong conduct.*";
P_HTM[6245]="*Channaṃ āpattisamuṭṭhānānaṃ ekena samuṭṭhānena samuṭṭhanti—**They originate in one way:*";
P_HTM[6246]="*vācato samuṭṭhanti, na kāyato na cittato.**from speech, not from body or mind.*";
P_HTM[6247]="*Catunnaṃ adhikaraṇānaṃ, āpattādhikaraṇaṃ.**They are legal issues arising from an offense.*";
P_HTM[6248]="*Sattannaṃ samathānaṃ tīhi samathehi sammanti—**They are settled in three ways:*";
P_HTM[6249]="*siyā sammukhāvinayena ca paṭiññātakaraṇena ca, siyā sammukhāvinayena ca tiṇavatthārakena ca.**they may be settled by resolution face-to-face and by acting according to what has been admitted; or they may be settled by resolution face-to-face and by covering over as if with grass.*";
P_HTM[6250]="*Tatiyena āpattisamuṭṭhānena kati āpattiyo āpajjati?**How many offenses does one commit through the third origin of offenses?*";
P_HTM[6251]="*Tatiyena āpattisamuṭṭhānena pañca āpattiyo āpajjati.**Five:*";
P_HTM[6252]="*Bhikkhu kappiyasaññī saṃvidahitvā kuṭiṃ karoti adesitavatthukaṃ pamāṇātikkantaṃ sārambhaṃ aparikkamanaṃ. Payoge dukkaṭaṃ;**when a monk—perceiving it as allowable and having agreed with others—builds a hut whose site has not been approved, which exceeds the right size, where harm will be done, and which lacks a space on all sides, then for the effort there is an offense of wrong conduct;*";
P_HTM[6253]="*ekaṃ piṇḍaṃ anāgate āpatti thullaccayassa;**when one piece is left to complete the hut, he commits a serious offense;*";
P_HTM[6254]="*tasmiṃ piṇḍe āgate āpatti saṅghādisesassa.**when the last piece is finished, he commits an offense entailing suspension;*";
P_HTM[6255]="*Bhikkhu kappiyasaññī paṇītabhojanāni attano atthāya viññāpetvā bhuñjati, āpatti pācittiyassa.**when a monk, perceiving it as allowable, eats fine foods that he himself has asked for, he commits an offense entailing confession;*";
P_HTM[6256]="*Bhikkhu kappiyasaññī bhikkhuniyā vosāsantiyā na nivāretvā bhuñjati, āpatti pāṭidesanīyassa—**when a monk, perceiving it as allowable, eats without having restrained a nun who is giving directions, he commits an offense entailing acknowledgment.*";
P_HTM[6257]="*tatiyena āpattisamuṭṭhānena imā pañca āpattiyo āpajjati.* **";
P_HTM[6258]="*Tā āpattiyo catunnaṃ vipattīnaṃ kati vipattiyo bhajanti …pe…**When it comes to these offenses, to how many of the four kinds of failure do they belong? …*";
P_HTM[6259]="*sattannaṃ samathānaṃ katihi samathehi sammanti?**Through how many of the seven principles for settling legal issues are they settled?*";
P_HTM[6260]="*Tā āpattiyo catunnaṃ vipattīnaṃ dve vipattiyo bhajanti—**They belong to two kinds of failure:*";
P_HTM[6261]="*siyā sīlavipattiṃ, siyā ācāravipattiṃ.**they may be failure in morality; they may be failure in conduct.*";
P_HTM[6262]="*Sattannaṃ āpattikkhandhānaṃ pañcahi āpattikkhandhehi saṅgahitā—**They are found in five classes of offenses:*";
P_HTM[6263]="*siyā saṅghādisesāpattikkhandhena, siyā thullaccayāpattikkhandhena, siyā pācittiyāpattikkhandhena, siyā pāṭidesanīyāpattikkhandhena, siyā dukkaṭāpattikkhandhena.**they may be in the class of offenses entailing suspension; they may be in the class of serious offenses; they may be in the class of offenses entailing confession; they may be in the class of offenses entailing acknowledgment; they may be in the class of offenses of wrong conduct.*";
P_HTM[6264]="*Channaṃ āpattisamuṭṭhānānaṃ ekena samuṭṭhānena samuṭṭhanti—**They originate in one way:*";
P_HTM[6265]="*kāyato ca vācato ca samuṭṭhanti, na cittato.**from body and speech, not from mind.*";
P_HTM[6266]="*Catunnaṃ adhikaraṇānaṃ, āpattādhikaraṇaṃ.**They are legal issues arising from an offense.*";
P_HTM[6267]="*Sattannaṃ samathānaṃ tīhi samathehi sammanti—**They are settled in three ways:*";
P_HTM[6268]="*siyā sammukhāvinayena ca paṭiññātakaraṇena ca, siyā sammukhāvinayena ca tiṇavatthārakena ca.**they may be settled by resolution face-to-face and by acting according to what has been admitted; or they may be settled by resolution face-to-face and by covering over as if with grass.*";
P_HTM[6269]="*Catutthena āpattisamuṭṭhānena kati āpattiyo āpajjati?**How many offenses does one commit through the fourth origin of offenses?*";
P_HTM[6270]="*Catutthena āpattisamuṭṭhānena cha āpattiyo āpajjati—**Six:*";
P_HTM[6271]="*bhikkhu methunaṃ dhammaṃ paṭisevati, āpatti pārājikassa;**when a monk has sexual intercourse, he commits an offense entailing expulsion;*";
P_HTM[6272]="*bhikkhu akappiyasaññī saññācikāya kuṭiṃ karoti adesitavatthukaṃ pamāṇātikkantaṃ sārambhaṃ aparikkamanaṃ, payoge dukkaṭaṃ;**when a monk—perceiving it as unallowable and by means of begging—builds a hut whose site has not been approved, which exceeds the right size, where harm will be done, and which lacks a space on all sides, then for the effort there is an offense of wrong conduct;*";
P_HTM[6273]="*ekaṃ piṇḍaṃ anāgate āpatti thullaccayassa;**when one piece is left to complete the hut, he commits a serious offense;*";
P_HTM[6274]="*tasmiṃ piṇḍe āgate āpatti saṅghādisesassa.**when the last piece is finished, he commits an offense entailing suspension;*";
P_HTM[6275]="*Bhikkhu akappiyasaññī vikāle bhojanaṃ bhuñjati, āpatti pācittiyassa.**when a monk, perceiving it as unallowable, eats cooked food at the wrong time, he commits an offense entailing confession;*";
P_HTM[6276]="*Bhikkhu akappiyasaññī aññātikāya bhikkhuniyā antaragharaṃ paviṭṭhāya hatthato khādanīyaṃ vā bhojanīyaṃ vā sahatthā paṭiggahetvā bhuñjati, āpatti pāṭidesanīyassa.**when a monk, perceiving it as unallowable, receives fresh or cooked food directly from an unrelated nun who has entered an inhabited area, and then eats it, he commits an offense entailing acknowledgment.*";
P_HTM[6277]="*Catutthena āpattisamuṭṭhānena imā cha āpattiyo āpajjati.* **";
P_HTM[6278]="*Tā āpattiyo catunnaṃ vipattīnaṃ kati vipattiyo bhajanti …pe…**When it comes to these offenses, to how many of the four kinds of failure do they belong? …*";
P_HTM[6279]="*sattannaṃ samathānaṃ katihi samathehi sammanti?**Through how many of the seven principles for settling legal issues are they settled?*";
P_HTM[6280]="*Tā āpattiyo catunnaṃ vipattīnaṃ dve vipattiyo bhajanti—**They belong to two kinds of failure:*";
P_HTM[6281]="*siyā sīlavipattiṃ, siyā ācāravipattiṃ.**they may be failure in morality; they may be failure in conduct.*";
P_HTM[6282]="*Sattannaṃ āpattikkhandhānaṃ chahi āpattikkhandhehi saṅgahitā—**They are found in six classes of offenses:*";
P_HTM[6283]="*siyā pārājikāpattikkhandhena, siyā saṅghādisesāpattikkhandhena, siyā thullaccayāpattikkhandhena, siyā pācittiyāpattikkhandhena, siyā pāṭidesanīyāpattikkhandhena, siyā dukkaṭāpattikkhandhena.**they may be in the class of offenses entailing expulsion; they may be in the class of offenses entailing suspension; they may be in the class of serious offenses; they may be in the class of offenses entailing confession; they may be in the class of offenses entailing acknowledgment; they may be in the class of offenses of wrong conduct.*";
P_HTM[6284]="*Channaṃ āpattisamuṭṭhānānaṃ ekena samuṭṭhānena samuṭṭhanti—**They originate in one way:*";
P_HTM[6285]="*kāyato ca cittato ca samuṭṭhanti, na vācato.**from body and mind, not from speech.*";
P_HTM[6286]="*Catunnaṃ adhikaraṇānaṃ, āpattādhikaraṇaṃ.**They are legal issues arising from an offense.*";
P_HTM[6287]="*Sattannaṃ samathānaṃ tīhi samathehi sammanti—**They are settled in three ways:*";
P_HTM[6288]="*siyā sammukhāvinayena ca paṭiññātakaraṇena ca, siyā sammukhāvinayena ca tiṇavatthārakena ca.**they may be settled by resolution face-to-face and by acting according to what has been admitted; or they may be settled by resolution face-to-face and by covering over as if with grass.*";
P_HTM[6289]="*Pañcamena āpattisamuṭṭhānena kati āpattiyo āpajjati?**How many offenses does one commit through the fifth origin of offenses?*";
P_HTM[6290]="*Pañcamena āpattisamuṭṭhānena cha āpattiyo āpajjati.**Six:*";
P_HTM[6291]="*Bhikkhu pāpiccho icchāpakato asantaṃ abhūtaṃ uttarimanussadhammaṃ ullapati, āpatti pārājikassa;**when a monk—having bad desires, overcome by desire—claims a non-existent, unreal superhuman quality, he commits an offense entailing expulsion;*";
P_HTM[6292]="*bhikkhu akappiyasaññī samādisati—“kuṭiṃ me karothā”ti. Tassa kuṭiṃ karonti adesitavatthukaṃ pamāṇātikkantaṃ sārambhaṃ aparikkamanaṃ. Payoge dukkaṭaṃ;**when a monk, perceiving it as unallowable, appoints someone to build him a hut, and they build a hut whose site has not been approved, which exceeds the right size, where harm will be done, and which lacks a space on all sides, then for the effort there is an offense of wrong conduct;*";
P_HTM[6293]="*ekaṃ piṇḍaṃ anāgate āpatti thullaccayassa;**when one piece is left to complete the hut, he commits a serious offense;*";
P_HTM[6294]="*tasmiṃ piṇḍe āgate āpatti saṅghādisesassa.**when the last piece is finished, he commits an offense entailing suspension;*";
P_HTM[6295]="*Bhikkhu akappiyasaññī anupasampannaṃ padaso dhammaṃ vāceti, āpatti pācittiyassa.**when a monk, perceiving it as unallowable, instructs a person who is not fully ordained to memorize the Teaching, he commits an offense entailing confession;*";
P_HTM[6296]="*Na khuṃsetukāmo na vambhetukāmo na maṅkukattukāmo davakamyatā hīnena hīnaṃ vadeti, āpatti dubbhāsitassa—**when—not wishing to revile, not wishing to insult, not wishing to humiliate, but wanting to have fun—one says what is low to one who is low, one commits an offense of wrong speech.*";
P_HTM[6297]="*pañcamena āpattisamuṭṭhānena imā cha āpattiyo āpajjati.* **";
P_HTM[6298]="*Tā āpattiyo catunnaṃ vipattīnaṃ kati vipattiyo bhajanti …pe…**When it comes to these offenses, to how many of the four kinds of failure do they belong? …*";
P_HTM[6299]="*sattannaṃ samathānaṃ katihi samathehi sammanti?**Through how many of the seven principles for settling legal issues are they settled?*";
P_HTM[6300]="*Tā āpattiyo catunnaṃ vipattīnaṃ dve vipattiyo bhajanti—**They belong to two kinds of failure:*";
P_HTM[6301]="*siyā sīlavipattiṃ, siyā ācāravipattiṃ.**they may be failure in morality; they may be failure in conduct.*";
P_HTM[6302]="*Sattannaṃ āpattikkhandhānaṃ chahi āpattikkhandhehi saṅgahitā—**They are found in six classes of offenses:*";
P_HTM[6303]="*siyā pārājikāpattikkhandhena, siyā saṅghādisesāpattikkhandhena, siyā thullaccayāpattikkhandhena, siyā pācittiyāpattikkhandhena, siyā dukkaṭāpattikkhandhena, siyā dubbhāsitāpattikkhandhena.**they may be in the class of offenses entailing expulsion; they may be in the class of offenses entailing suspension; they may be in the class of serious offenses; they may be in the class of offenses entailing confession; they may be in the class of offenses of wrong conduct; they may be in the class of offenses of wrong speech.*";
P_HTM[6304]="*Channaṃ āpattisamuṭṭhānānaṃ ekena samuṭṭhānena samuṭṭhanti—**They originate in one way:*";
P_HTM[6305]="*vācato ca cittato ca samuṭṭhanti, na kāyato.**from speech and mind, not from body.*";
P_HTM[6306]="*Catunnaṃ adhikaraṇānaṃ, āpattādhikaraṇaṃ.**They are legal issues arising from an offense.*";
P_HTM[6307]="*Sattannaṃ samathānaṃ tīhi samathehi sammanti—**They are settled in three ways:*";
P_HTM[6308]="*siyā sammukhāvinayena ca paṭiññātakaraṇena ca, siyā sammukhāvinayena ca tiṇavatthārakena ca.**they may be settled by resolution face-to-face and by acting according to what has been admitted; or they may be settled by resolution face-to-face and by covering over as if with grass.*";
P_HTM[6309]="*Chaṭṭhena āpattisamuṭṭhānena kati āpattiyo āpajjati?**How many offenses does one commit through the sixth origin of offenses?*";
P_HTM[6310]="*Chaṭṭhena āpattisamuṭṭhānena cha āpattiyo āpajjati—**Six:*";
P_HTM[6311]="*bhikkhu saṃvidahitvā bhaṇḍaṃ avaharati, āpatti pārājikassa;**when a monk, having agreed with others, takes goods, he commits a offense entailing expulsion;*";
P_HTM[6312]="*bhikkhu akappiyasaññī saṃvidahitvā kuṭiṃ karoti adesitavatthukaṃ pamāṇātikkantaṃ sārambhaṃ aparikkamanaṃ, payoge dukkaṭaṃ;**when a monk—perceiving it as unallowable and having agreed with others—builds a hut whose site has not been approved, which exceeds the right size, where harm will be done, and which lacks a space on all sides, then for the effort there is an offense of wrong conduct;*";
P_HTM[6313]="*ekaṃ piṇḍaṃ anāgate āpatti thullaccayassa;**when one piece is left to complete the hut, he commits a serious offense;*";
P_HTM[6314]="*tasmiṃ piṇḍe āgate, āpatti saṅghādisesassa.**when the last piece is finished, he commits an offense entailing suspension;*";
P_HTM[6315]="*Bhikkhu akappiyasaññī paṇītabhojanāni attano atthāya viññāpetvā bhuñjati, āpatti pācittiyassa.**when a monk, perceiving it as unallowable, eats fine foods that he himself has asked for, he commits an offense entailing confession;*";
P_HTM[6316]="*Bhikkhu akappiyasaññī bhikkhuniyā vosāsantiyā na nivāretvā bhuñjati, āpatti pāṭidesanīyassa—**when a monk, perceiving it as unallowable, eats without having restrained a nun who is giving directions, he commits an offense entailing acknowledgment.*";
P_HTM[6317]="*chaṭṭhena āpattisamuṭṭhānena imā cha āpattiyo āpajjati.* **";
